    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1R"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">H.E.S's Rooms.</p>
            <p rend="align(right)"><date>Feby 5<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1868</date>.</p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Rev S. Morais</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">My Dear Sir-</p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">Accompanying<lb/> please find the “resolutions”<lb/> I should wish
                to have made<lb/> them more elaborate but<lb/> time and the school prevented.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Do not hesitate to make<lb/> any change in them which<lb/> may seem
                advisable</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Yrs very truly</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)"><persName role="author">W. H. Williams</persName>.</p>
            <p>P.S.</p>
            <p>I showed them to <persName>Rev Mrss Beltteheim</persName><lb/> and
                        <persName>Buttenwefin<add>?</add></persName> they approve of them<lb/> but
                    <persName>Mr Beltteheim</persName> suggests there<lb/> should be more
                recognition of his<lb/> position as <hi rend="underline">Provost</hi>=</p>
            <pb n="1V"/>
            <p>at a special meeting of the Faculty of Maimonides College held<lb/> in consequence of
                the sad bereavement recently <del>lately</del> sustained by<lb/> the house of
                    <placeName>Israel</placeName>, the following preamble and resolutions were<lb/>
                unanimously adopted</p>
            <p>Whereas the demise of the <persName>Revd Isaac Leeser</persName> is deemed by<lb/>
                each of us a national loss, and whereas it is our conviction<lb/> that the
                establishing of this institution was principally due<lb/> to the unremitting
                exertions of our late colaborer, and to his<lb/> constant advocacy of religious
                education, <sic>therefre</sic></p>
            <p>Resolved that we express our feelings of deep sorrow at the<lb/> loss of a man so
                zealous for the moral welfare of his people,<lb/> so energetic in promoting the
                culture of human knowledge, so<lb/> efficient as a professor, so exemplary assiduous
                in the discharge<lb/> of <add>all</add> his duties.</p>
            <p>Resolved that we <del>gladly</del>
                <add>?</add> bearing our testimony to the unborn<add>?</add> kindness and<lb/>
                courtesy that marked his official relations with us, and to<lb/> his timely and
                useful suggestions as <del>the</del> Provost of this College</p>
            <p>Resolved that we will <add>ever</add> cherish his memory as that of a friend,<lb/>
                and teach <del>our</del> the students of this institution to revere his
                    <del>memory</del> name</p>
            <p>Resolved that these resolutions be published in all Jewish <add>one of our
                    dailies</add><lb/> periodicals; <del>and</del></p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">
                <persName role="author">S. Morais</persName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">Sect Pt.</p>
            <p>
                <date>February 5<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1868</date>
            </p>
        </body>
